================================================================================
  WiiFin ← GRRLIB patch: reentrant GRRLIB_Init()/GRRLIB_Exit()
================================================================================
  GRRLIB pinned to commit 1945955f941ff945f282c0993c1f71b722e6310a
  (https://github.com/GRRLIB/GRRLIB), applied to
  GRRLIB/GRRLIB/GRRLIB_core.c during the Docker image build (Dockerfile.dev)
  before `make install`.

  Background
  ----------
  WiiFin hands GX ownership back and forth between GRRLIB (menus/UI) and
  MPlayer CE (video playback) on every play/stop cycle: when playback starts,
  MPlayer's mpgxInit() calls back into WiiFin's g_wiifin_grrlib_cleanup_cb,
  which calls GRRLIB_Exit(); when playback stops, WiiFin calls GRRLIB_Init()
  again to reclaim GX for the UI (see source/player/WiiPlayer.h's own
  documented contract: "the caller MUST call GRRLIB_Init() to reclaim the
  GX"). This is original, intentional design -- confirmed present verbatim
  in the v0.1.1 release source, not something introduced by this fork.

  The problem: GRRLIB_Init()/GRRLIB_Exit() (GRRLIB_core.c) are guarded to
  only ever do real work ONCE, for the lifetime of the process --
  `GRRLIB_Init()` doc comment says "Call this once at the beginning your
  code", `GRRLIB_Exit()`'s says "Ensure this function is only ever called
  once". This guard logic dates to GRRLIB commit ccb6ec7 (2009) -- it is
  not a recent regression, and was already present in whatever GRRLIB
  build the original release was compiled against.

  In practice: the FIRST time video playback stops, GRRLIB_Exit() runs for
  real -- frees xfb[0]/xfb[1]/gp_fifo, destroys the one global FreeType
  library handle (GRRLIB_ExitTTF() -> FT_Done_FreeType()). The very next
  GRRLIB_Init() call is then a silent no-op (`is_setup` is already true
  from app startup), so none of xfb[]/gp_fifo/FreeType ever get
  reallocated. From that point on, WiiFin is issuing GX/FreeType calls
  against freed pointers and a destroyed FreeType instance -- a genuine
  use-after-free. Symptom on real hardware only (Dolphin's GX/timing
  emulation doesn't reliably reproduce it): intermittent hang inside
  GX_DrawDone() (GRRLIB_Render()) or a crash inside font/texture reload,
  shortly after the first video is stopped. Location shifts between builds
  because it's memory corruption, not a fixed code-path bug.

  Fix
  ---
  Rework the one-shot guards so repeated Init/Exit cycles behave correctly:
  drop GRRLIB_Exit()'s separate function-local `done` static and its
  `is_setup == false` OR-condition, and have GRRLIB_Exit() itself clear
  `is_setup` at the point it used to set `done = true`. GRRLIB_Init()'s own
  `if (is_setup == true) return 0;` guard is untouched -- it now correctly
  re-runs the full setup (video mode, xfb allocation, GX pipeline config,
  TTF, system font) every time GRRLIB_Exit() has run since the last Init,
  exactly the semantics WiiFin's playback-transition code already assumed.

  None of the actual setup/teardown logic in either function is touched by
  this patch -- only the guard conditions controlling whether that logic
  runs.

--- a/GRRLIB/GRRLIB/GRRLIB_core.c
+++ b/GRRLIB/GRRLIB/GRRLIB_core.c
@@ -225,11 +225,10 @@
  * and only if the setup function has been called.
  */
 void  GRRLIB_Exit (void) {
-    static bool done = false;
-    if (done == true || is_setup == false) {
+    if (is_setup == false) {
         return;
     }
-    done = true;
+    is_setup = false;

     // Allow write access to the full screen
     GX_SetClipMode( GX_CLIP_DISABLE );
